# Issue Writing Rules

Use this rule when creating or refining GitHub issues.

## Core Rule

An issue should be executable without requiring others to guess its core intent.

## Every Good Issue Should Include

- **Title** — Clear and specific (e.g. “Parse voice phrase into exercise, set, weight, reps, notes” not “Improve voice”).
- **Objective** — What is being built or fixed and why it matters (e.g. “So the app can capture one set from a spoken phrase and validate before save”).
- **Scope (in scope)** — What will be done in this issue (e.g. “ParseExerciseSkill: input raw text, output structured { exercise, setNumber, weight, reps, notes }”).
- **Out of scope** (when relevant) — What will not be done here (e.g. “No superset grouping in this issue; no persistence yet”).
- **Dependencies** — e.g. “Depends on #N.” If the issue touches voice pipeline or session persistence, note dependency on any existing agent/skill or API.
- **Acceptance criteria** — Concrete and verifiable (see 111-acceptance-criteria-rules.mdc). For GymVoice, prefer criteria like “Given phrase X, ParseExerciseSkill returns Y” or “Given incomplete set, app asks for confirmation and does not save until confirmed.”
- **Relevant notes** — Only when useful (e.g. reference to Business Logic or Technical Documentation for rules that apply).

## Good Issue Characteristics

A good issue is:

- small enough to execute
- specific enough to avoid interpretation drift
- aligned with the current MVP
- testable and reviewable
- explicit about what success means

## Avoid

Avoid issues that are:

- vague (“Make voice better”)
- too broad (“Implement entire workout flow”)
- secretly multiple tasks (“Add voice and history”)
- architecture-heavy without need
- missing acceptance criteria
- describing only code changes without the actual problem or user/system behavior being solved

## GymVoice References

- Process: TASK_EXECUTION_WORKFLOW.md, PRD; planning: MILESTONES.md, MVP_PLAN.md.
- Domain: Business Logic doc for flows and rules; PRD for MVP scope. If the issue touches voice pipeline or session persistence, note dependency on any existing agent/skill or API.

## Final Rule

If the implementer would need multiple clarification rounds to understand the intended result, the issue is not ready.
